\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Regulator's final period offer
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
At time 
\begin_inset Formula $T,$
\end_inset

 the regulator knows the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\se_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pub_{i}$
\end_inset

 and the conditional distributions of 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\env_{i}$
\end_inset

 and can offer a payment 
\begin_inset Formula $\offer_{i}>0$
\end_inset

 to the landowner in exchange for conserving the land.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Given the multivariate normal assumption, there is a probability that the
 regulator might want to set 
\begin_inset Formula $\offer_{i}<0$
\end_inset

 to induce a landowner to develop land the landowner would prefer to conserve,
 but this option is not considered in this analysis.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Under conditions described below, the regulator infers that there is an
 upper bound (
\begin_inset Formula $\ubPriv$
\end_inset

) for the private development value of land that has not yet been converted.
 Since this is the last period, the landowner will accept the offer if 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv_{i}\leq\offer_{i}$
\end_inset

 .
 The regulator will not make an offer above 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{\priv}$
\end_inset

 because the regulator could lower the offer to 
\begin_inset Formula $\ubPriv$
\end_inset

 and maintain perfect certainty that the parcel will be conserved.
 The regulator's expected payoff
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Strictly speaking, this expression is the expected payoff assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $\offer_{i}\leq\ubPriv$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 for a parcel is the probability the parcel is conserved in the second period
 times the expected payoff conditional on conservation plus the (known)
 public development value times the probability the parcel is developed
 or 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\payEnd\left(\offer_{i},\se_{i}\pub_{i},\Sigma\right)=\intop_{-\infty}^{\offer_{i}}\intop_{-\infty}^{\infty}\left(\env-\offer_{i}\right)f_{\env|\se,\priv}\left(\env|\se_{i},\priv\right)d\env f_{\priv|\se,\pub}\left(\priv|\se_{i},\pub_{i}\right)dp+\intop_{\offer_{i}}^{\infty}\pub_{i}f_{\priv|\se,\pub}\left(\priv|\se_{i},\pub_{i}\right)dp
\]

\end_inset

Note that this expression is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $\ubPriv$
\end_inset

, so the upper bound affects the problem only through the constraint that
 
\begin_inset Formula $\offer_{i}\leq\ubPriv$
\end_inset

.
 As shown in the appendix, under the multivariate normal assumption, this
 expression can be simplified to
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\payEnd\left(\offer_{i},\se_{i}\pub_{i},\Sigma\right)=-\sigma_{\env}\sigma_{\priv}\left(\rho_{\env\priv}-\sigShrS\rho_{\se\priv}\right)f_{\priv|\se,\pub}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i},\pub_{i}\right)+\left(\meanE+\sigShrS\sigma_{\env}\se_{i}-\offer_{i}\right)F_{\priv|\se,\pub}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i},\pub_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset

The Lagrangian for the regulator's problem is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\mathcal{L}\left(\offer_{i},\lambda;\se_{i},\pub_{i},\Sigma,\ubPriv_{i}\right)=\payEnd\left(\offer_{i},\se_{i}\pub_{i},\Sigma\right)-\lambda_{1}\left(\offer_{i}-\ubPriv_{i}\right)+\lambda_{2}\offer_{i}
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{1}$
\end_inset

 is the Lagrange multiplier on the upper bound and 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_{2}$
\end_inset

 is the multiplier on the nonnegativity constraint.
 The first-order condition for an interior solution is
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{\partial\payEnd}{\partial\offer_{i}}\left(\offer_{i},\se_{i}\pub_{i},\Sigma\right)=-\sigma_{\env}\sigma_{\priv}\left(\rho_{\env\priv}-\sigShrS\rho_{\se\priv}\right)\frac{df_{\priv|\se}}{d\priv}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)+\left(\meanE+\sigShrS\sigma_{\env}\se_{i}-\offer_{i}\right)f_{\priv|\se}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)-F_{\priv|\se}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)=0.
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\priv_{i}|\se_{i}$
\end_inset

 has a normal distribution, we know that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{df_{\priv|\se,\pub}}{d\priv}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)=-\frac{\offer_{i}-\mu_{\priv|\se}}{\sigma_{\priv|\se}^{2}}f_{\priv|\se}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)
\]

\end_inset

giving us
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\overbrace{\underbrace{f_{\priv|\se}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)}_{\mbox{Pr marginal}}\underbrace{\left(\frac{\sigma_{\env}\left(\rho_{\env\priv}-\sigShrS\rho_{\se\priv}\right)}{\sigma_{\priv}\left(1-\rho_{\se\priv}^{2}\right)}\left(\offer_{i}-\mu_{\priv|\se}\right)+\meanE+\sigShrS\sigma_{\env}\se_{i}-\offer_{i}\right)}_{\mbox{conditional expected gain}}}^{\mbox{marginal benefit}}=\overbrace{F_{\priv|\se}\left(\offer_{i}|\se_{i}\right)}^{\mbox{marginal cost}}.\label{eq:p2FOC}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

